\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Problem Definition}

Every minute, thousands of industrial control systems silently regulate the physical world — managing the pressure in boiler pipelines, balancing fluid levels in treatment tanks, and governing the thermal cycles of power turbines. These systems are the operational foundation of critical infrastructure, and their failure is not an abstraction: it is a blackout, a contaminated water supply, or an explosion. The growing integration of industrial control systems (ICS) with digital communication networks has introduced a profound and asymmetric cybersecurity threat. Unlike attacks on conventional IT systems, where the objective is to compromise data, attacks on ICS target the \emph{physical process itself} — manipulating actuator setpoints, injecting false sensor readings, and driving the controlled system toward degraded or catastrophic states while appearing operationally normal to conventional monitoring tools.

The fundamental challenge of ICS anomaly detection is that a sophisticated adversary does not need to trigger any individual alarm. Stealthy attacks — such as the Stuxnet worm that targeted Siemens PLCs in Iranian centrifuges, or the coordinated actuator manipulation that disrupted Ukrainian power distribution in 2015 and 2016 — operate precisely within individually plausible sensor ranges. Each measured value appears normal in isolation; the attack only becomes visible when the \emph{expected dynamic relationship between variables} is examined across time. A pressure sensor reading of 4.2 bar may be perfectly normal in one operating context and an anomaly in another, depending on the simultaneous states of level, flow, and temperature throughout the interconnected control loops. No static threshold and no per-channel rule can reliably distinguish these cases.

This gap motivates the use of a \textbf{digital twin surrogate} — a learned model of the physical process that can simulate what the system \emph{should be doing} at every moment, given the history of control commands and operating conditions. By comparing the surrogate's predicted process variable trajectories against the actual sensor readings in real time, deviations that span multiple channels and accumulate over time can be detected as anomaly signals even when no single measurement crosses a threshold. This approach has been demonstrated for cyber-physical water systems (Homaei et al., 2026) and represents the state of the art in model-based ICS security monitoring.

\vspace{0.3cm}

This project develops a physics-informed closed-loop data drivern digital twin as simulator and generator for the \textbf{HAI 23.05} (Hardware-in-the-Loop Augmented ICS Security) testbed (HAI-Dataset-v4.0). The HAI testbed is one of the most representative publicly available ICS security benchmarks, comprising three interconnected physical processes which are: a boiler system (P1), a turbine system (P2), and a water treatment system (P3) and hardware-in-the-loop simulation (P4) controlled by Emerson Ovation DCS, GE Mark VIe DCS, and Siemens S7-300 PLC controllers, as illustrated in Figure 1.

