The third source is a domain-informed causal graph of the boiler system, motivated by recent work on causal digital twins for cyber-physical security. The physics-related energy and mass flow paths — spanning hydrodynamic and thermodynamic interactions across the plant — that underpin the causal structure are captured in Figure 4, justifying the need for a causal graph to encode the system's behavioural laws. The graph was derived from HAI sensor data using time-delayed mutual information (TDMI) and cross-correlation analysis, refined with physical domain knowledge, and yields 83 directed edges organized into three causal layers: L0 (DCS logic: sensor $\rightarrow$ actuator), L1 (direct physical: actuator $\rightarrow$ sensor), and L2 (two-hop physical: actuator $\rightarrow$ intermediate $\rightarrow$ sensor). Together, these three sources form a unified representation enabling the model to learn not only correlative patterns but also the underlying causal mechanisms governing system behaviour under both normal operation and attack conditions.

