\subsubsection{Post-hoc Anomaly Detection}

To enhance detection performance without modifying the predictive model, we apply post-hoc anomaly detection techniques on the prediction residuals. These methods operate on top of the GRU outputs and do not require retraining, making them suitable for deployment scenarios.

The baseline approach uses a fixed global threshold on the residual (MSE). While this method achieves strong separability (AUROC ≈ 0.899), it suffers from poor precision under class imbalance, as reflected by a low average precision (0.091) and F1-score (0.487).

To address this limitation, we apply Isolation Forest trained exclusively on normal validation residuals. This post-hoc refinement significantly improves detection performance, increasing the F1-score from 0.487 to 0.571 and the average precision from 0.091 to 0.555, while maintaining comparable AUROC. This indicates that the predictive model already produces well-ranked anomaly scores, and the improvement stems primarily from better decision boundaries rather than enhanced separability.

