Importantly, these improvements are achieved without retraining the predictive model, highlighting the flexibility of post-hoc anomaly detection.

Furthermore, the effectiveness of these methods is closely tied to the structured residual behavior introduced by the causal model. By enforcing physically meaningful dependencies and time lags, the causal formulation ensures that prediction errors are primarily driven by true deviations in system dynamics rather than modeling limitations.

Overall, the results show that post-hoc detection transforms high-quality prediction errors into practical and reliable anomaly detection signals, bridging the gap between predictive modeling and real-world deployment.
