\subsubsection{Threshold Analysis and Deployment Behavior}

To evaluate practical deployment performance, anomaly scores derived from prediction residuals are analyzed using a fixed alert threshold.

The effectiveness of threshold-based detection depends strongly on the structure of the prediction error. In the non-causal baseline, elevated residuals may arise from modeling limitations, particularly for variables with long delays, making threshold selection less reliable. In contrast, the causal model produces consistently low residuals under normal operation and structured increases under attack scenarios, resulting in clearer separation between normal and abnormal behavior.

Figure~\ref{fig:residual_boxplot} shows the distribution of anomaly scores across different scenarios. Under normal conditions, residual values remain significantly below the threshold, indicating a low false alarm rate. In contrast, the AP\_with scenario produces substantially higher residuals that clearly exceed the threshold, enabling reliable detection. The AP\_no and AE\_no scenarios exhibit intermediate behavior, reflecting moderate deviations that may not always trigger immediate alerts.

